 Swimming Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Esther Williams Trophy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin\n| colwidth = 30em\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = H\u00e1y\n | first = Peter\n | authorlink = Peter H\u00e1y (Canadian author, publisher and bookseller)\n | year = 1991\n | title = MGM: When the Lion Roars\n | edition = 1st\n | publisher = Turner Publishing, Inc\n | location = Atlanta, Georgia\n | isbn = 978-1-878685-04-9\n | oclc = 499304130\n | url = https://books.google.com/?id=WxEIAQAAMAAJ\n | accessdate = July 30, 2010\n | ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | title = The Encyclopedia of Women and Sports\n | last = Sherrow\n | first = Victoria\n | year = 1996\n | publisher = ABC-CLIO\n | location = Santa Barbara, California\n | isbn = 978-0-87436-826-0\n | oclc = 34658767\n | url = https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofwo00sher\n | accessdate = July 30, 2010\n | ref = harv\n }}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Williams\n | first = Esther\n | year = 1999\n | title = The Million Dollar Mermaid: An Autobiography\n | type = Autobiography\n | edition = First\n | publisher = Simon & Schuster\n | location = New York\n | isbn = 978-0-15-601135-8\n | oclc = 43706619\n | url = https://books.google.com/?id=8Rspg9YX9tcC&printsec=frontcover<!-- a reprint that has online preview -->\n | accessdate = July 30, 2010\n | ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Wayne\n | first = Jane Ellen\n | year = 2003\n | title = The Golden Girls of MGM: Greta Garbo, Joan Crawford, Lana Turner, Judy Garland, Ava Gardner, Grace Kelly, and Others\n | edition = First\n | publisher = Carroll & Graf Publishers\n | location = New York  <!-- Originally published: London : Robson, 2002 -->\n | isbn = 978-0-7867-1303-5\n | oclc = 54010001\n | url = https://books.google.com/?id=TwMw7HsE_WMC&printsec=frontcover\n | accessdate = July 30, 2010\n | ref = harv\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{official website|http://www.esther-williams.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|930565}}\n* [http://www.estherwilliamspools.com/ Esther Williams Swimming Pools website]\n* [http://film.virtual-history.com/person.php?personid=4911 Photographs of Esther Williams]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070526045456/http://www.thegoldenyears.org/williams.html ''The Golden Years'']\n* [http://www.esthersfollies.com/ Vaudeville theater named in honor of Esther Williams]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Esther}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Inglewood, California]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:American female swimmers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American women in business]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles City College alumni]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer contract players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Inglewood, California]]\n[[Category:Stroke survivors]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:20th-century businesswomen]]\n[[Category:Women memoirists]]\n", "name_user": "181.10.97.208", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esther_Williams"}
{"title_page": "Rana's Wedding", "text_new": "{{short description|2002 film}}\n{{Advert|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Rana's Wedding\n| image          = Rana's_Wedding.jpg\n| caption        = Poster\n| director       = [[Hany Abu-Assad]]\n| producer       = Bero Beyer and George Ibrahim\n| writer         = Ihab lamy and [[Liana Badr]]\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| editing        = Denise Janzee\n| starring       = [[Clara Khoury]], Khalifa Natour and Ismael Dabbagh\n| released       = {{Film date|2002}}\n| music          = Mariecke Van Der Linden and Bashar Abd Rabou\n| cinematography = Brigit Hillenius\n| distributor    = Arab Film Distribution\n| runtime        = 86 minutes\n| country        = Palestine\n| language       = Arabic\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $10,604<ref name=\"mojo\" /> (US)<!-- box office gross for US only, worldwide total not given -->\n}}\n'''''Rana's Wedding''''', also known as '''''Jerusalem, Another Day''''' (Arabic, \u0627\u0644\u0642\u062f\u0633 \u0641\u064a \u064a\u0648\u0645 \u0623\u062e\u0631 ), is a Palestinian film released in 2002, produced in partnership with the [[Netherlands]] and funded by the Palestinian Film Foundation. The film was shot in [[Jerusalem]] under the direction of  the Palestinian Director [[Hany Abu-Assad]] who is one of the first Palestinian film directors to reach [[Cannes Film Festival]] with his film, that was selected for screening at the [[International Critics' Week]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.itvs.org/about/global-perspectives-project/advisory-board |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512130925/http://itvs.org/about/global-perspectives-project/advisory-board |archive-date=2012-05-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"albawaba\">{{cite web|url=http://www.albawaba.com/entertainment/%E2%80%98rana%E2%80%99s-wedding%E2%80%99-opens-arab-presence-cannes-film-fest|title=\u2018Rana\u2019s Wedding\u2019 Opens Arab Presence at Cannes Film Fest|date=19 May 2002|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref> The film was also screened at multiple film festivals worldwide and received many excellent international reviews and awards. ''Rana's Wedding'' was able to present the [[Palestinian-Israeli conflict]] in an exceptional and compelling way, by using [[romance (love)|romance]] and [[dark comedy]] genres which left the audience astonished by this unique approach, that was able to portray, (through the couples marriage drama) a vivid image of a Palestinian's daily struggle, towards living a somewhat normal life.\n\n==Plot==\nA 17-year-old girl called Rana is subjected to a crucial life-changing decision at a very young age. Her father decides to leave Palestine and relocate to Egypt, due to the chaotic working and living conditions, to try to maintain a decent living to support his family. Rana wakes up one day and finds a letter from her father informing her about his difficult decision adding to it, he also involves her in his plans and provides her with two choices,<ref name=\"bostonglobe\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.boston.com/2004-03-12/ae/29207514_1_ihab-lamey-liana-badr-clara-khoury|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130118081234/http://articles.boston.com/2004-03-12/ae/29207514_1_ihab-lamey-liana-badr-clara-khoury|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 January 2013|title='Rana's Wedding' quietly marries passion, politics|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref> either to travel with him to Egypt and carry on with her education there under his watchful eye, or stay in Palestine and marry to make sure that someone is guarding her in his absence. Although the options seem fairly reasonable, there is a twist, her father will only allow her to marry one of the men that he has mentioned on a list with the letter, because they are the most reputable and trustworthy men in Jerusalem, as well as, she has to take that critical decision just 10 hours before her father departs from Palestine.<ref name=\"popmatters\">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/ranas-wedding|title=Rana's Wedding (2002)|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nRana is left shocked and disappointed with the options, after reading the letter she decides to run away from home in search of her lover Khalil that her father does not approve of because of his career, therefore, does not include him in the list of people she can marry.<ref name=\"bostonglobe\" /> Rana desperately searches for Khalil leaving no home, family or friend unasked about his whereabouts to inform him about her critical situation. As she searches for him she is faced with many challenges along the way from Israeli soldiers, road blocks and physical conflicts between Palestinian and Israeli soldiers.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C04E7DE1739F931A1575BC0A9659C8B63|title=Movie Review - 'Rana's Wedding' |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref> After hours of searching she finally finds his location and rushes to him, finding him in the theatre, working on directing one of his plays.\n\nAt last she finds him and tells him everything she has been through the past few hours, and confidently asks him for his hand in marriage, rushing him to take a decision in order to find a sheikh to marry them before her father sets off. Together they set out on an even longer journey to reach the sheikh and her father to approve of their marriage. They were able to find the sheikh and drove him to her father\u2019s house to convince him of the marriage, that he could not object to without any rightful excuse according to Islamic law, the sheikh supported Rana's decision and told her father that the marriage must proceed.<ref name=\"rogerebert\">{{cite web|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20040130/REVIEWS/401300304|title=Rana's Wedding Movie Review & Film Summary (2004) | website = RogerEbert.com | authorlink = Roger Ebert |first=Roger|last=Ebert|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref> Her father giving into her wishes unwillingly approves, Rana and Khalil then set out on another extremely tiresome mission, getting their papers and preparing themselves for their wedding ceremony.<ref name=\"filmthreat\">http://www.filmthreat.com/reviews/4693/</ref>\n\nAt the end tension rises when the wedding is held at Rana's father's house while the sheikh has not shown up to do the ceremony and her dad is getting ready to leave. As she waits restlessly she finds out that the sheikh is stuck at a road block. Her father gets furious and waits no longer, ordering her to come with him in her wedding dress, leaving for Egypt. Riding in the car with her father and her family they pressure and persuade her father to go to the road block for his daughter, finally agreeing they arrive at the road block. When her father and Khalil read their vows in the car, her dad sympathetically gives her away to the man she loves, ending the love story with a heart-warming celebration on the streets of Jerusalem. \n                                  \nThe film ends with the words of Palestinian poet, [[Mahmoud Darwish]]:\n{{quote|text=Here on the slopes before sunset and at the gun-mouth of time,\nNear orchards deprived of their shadows,<br />\nWe do what prisoners do,<br />\nWhat the unemployed do:<br />\nWe nurture hope.|sign=Mahmoud Darwish<ref name=\"popmatters\" />}}\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Clara Khoury]] as Rana\n* Khalifa Natour as Khalil\n* Ismael Dabbagh as Ramzy \n* Zuher Fahoum as Father\n* Bushra Karaman as Grandmother\n\n==Production==\nThe film was shot in [[East Jerusalem]], [[Ramallah]], [[State of Palestine|Palestine]]. Produced in collaboration with the [[Netherlands]] and funded by the Palestinian Film Foundation.<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\">{{cite web|url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ranas_wedding_jerusalem_another_day |title= Rana's Wedding: Jerusalem, Another Day|publisher= [[Fandango Media]] | website = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date= December 29, 2018 }}</ref> It was filmed  during a critical time in the early months of the [[second Palestinian intifada]]. [[Hany Abu-Assad]] in an interview with journalist Sabah Haider, discusses the challenges he faced when producing the film \"For sure the intifada influenced the production because at the end of the film, reality is stronger than fiction. The occupation, the checkpoints \u2014 you don\u2019t want them to interfere with your story but the ugliness of occupation influenced the look of film. As much as you might not want occupation to influence the making of the film, at the end it does influence it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electronicintifada.net/content/palestinian-cinema-cause-interview-hany-abu-assad/8708|title=\"Palestinian cinema is a cause\": an interview with Hany Abu-Assad|first=|last=matthew|date=8 March 2010|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nAccording to the website [[Box Office Mojo]], in 2003 ''Rana's Wedding'' was ranked out of the top 50 wedding genre films produced in that year, and received a world ranking of 1108 in [[foreign films]]. The film was able to generate $10,604 after 1 year of release, screening in film festivals around the world.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ranaswedding.htm|title=Rana's Wedding (2003) | website = [[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher= |access-date= 30 November 2016 }}</ref> It was selected for screening at the International critics week in 2002 at the [[Cannes Film Festival]].{{Citation needed|date = August 2015}}\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film ''Rana's Wedding'' was reviewed by many notable newspapers, websites and critics and overall received pleasing reviews.\n* ''Rana's Wedding'' was reviewed by [[Stephen Holden]] for ''[[The New York Times]]'' in 2003, discussing the plot and providing the film with great support to increase viewers interest towards this unique story.<ref name=\"nytimes\" />\n* It was reviewed by [[Al Bawaba]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albawaba.com/en/|title=Middle East News & Arab Headlines From A Local Perspective - Al Bawaba|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref> 2002, who identified it as one of the first Palestinian films to influence the Arabic films being screened at [[Cannes]] and was able to increase the Arab presence in the festival.<ref name=\"albawaba\" />\n* An article written by Janice Page in 2004 found at ''Boston''.com article collection, evaluates and supports the film with a great review.<ref name=\"bostonglobe\" />\n* ''[[About.com]]'', rated ''Rana's Wedding'', 3.5 stars out of 5, based on a review written by J\u00fcrgen Fauth, supporting the movie and evaluating its plot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldfilm.about.com/cs/filmsmiddleeast1/fr/ranaswedding.htm|title=Rana's Wedding|access-date=30 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201080108/http://worldfilm.about.com/cs/filmsmiddleeast1/fr/ranaswedding.htm|archive-date=1 December 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* On ''[[Rotten Tomatoes]]'' the film has an approval rating of 93% based on reviews from 28 critics, with an average rating of 7.2/10. The website's critical consensus states: \"A poignant drama that offers a look at what it is like to live in occupied Palestine.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\" />\n* On the website ''[[Metacritic]]'' the film has a score of 71 out of 100 based on reviews from 19 critics.<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web |url= http://www.metacritic.com/movie/ranas-wedding |title= Rana's Wedding |publisher= [[CBS Interactive]] | website = [[Metacritic]] |access-date= December 29, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n'''Awards'''\n* Won Grand Prize in Cologne  Mediterranean Film Festival, and [[Clara Khoury]] as best actress in (2002).<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web | url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0305229/awards |title= Rana's Wedding |date= 7 August 2003 |publisher= |work= IMDb |access-date=30 November 2016 }}</ref>\n* [[Clara Khoury]] won best actress from [[Marrakech International Film Festival]] in (2002).<ref name=\"imdb\" />\n* Won the Golden Antigone award from Montpellier Mediterranean Film Festival in (2002) <ref name=\"imdb\" />\n* Won the Golden Anchor award from [[Haifa International Film Festival]] in (2003) <ref name=\"imdb\" />\n* Won the [[Nestor Almendros]] for courage in film making, Human Rights Watch International Film Festival in (2003) \n'''Nominations'''\n* Nominated for the Golden star award from [[Marrakech International Film Festival]] in (2002)<ref name=\"imdb\" />\n* Nominated for the Golden Alexander Award by the [[Thessaloniki Film Festival]] in (2002)<ref name=\"imdb\" />\n* Nominated by [[Buenos Aires International Festival of Independent Cinema]] for Best Film in (2003) <ref name=\"imdb\" />\n* Nominated for Golden Dolphin award by [[Festr\u00f3ia - Tr\u00f3ia International Film Festival]] in (2003) <ref name=\"imdb\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n* ''Rana\u2019s Wedding'' is considered to be the first film that approaches and show cases the [[Palestinian-Israeli conflict]] in a novel way, leaving viewers astonished by this unique approach, because the film did not incorporate the common styles of films that discuss life circumstances in [[State of Palestine|Palestine]].<ref name=\"filmthreat\" /> In which they would always focus on tragic plots that contain similar content of war, murder, hunger and destruction. Instead ''Rana\u2019s Wedding'' portrayed all these events but in an indirect and compelling way, through a love story, and amazingly did not reduce the intensity of the Palestinian Israeli conflict. Through a plot that was able to portray how people still try to live and try to create an everyday normal life, despite the numbers that die in [[State of Palestine|Palestine]] each day. People still laugh, hope, worship, love, work, care for one other, sing and dance, and finally try to have a normal wedding that\u2019s not so normal to many of us.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiritualityandpractice.com/films/films.php?id=6542|title=Rana's Wedding - Film Reviews - Films - Spirituality & Practice|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref> ''Rana\u2019s Wedding'' is just filled with pure heart felt emotions and through the movements of the couple one is able to witness all the different events that take place in [[Jerusalem]], both the joyful and heart-breaking. A film that truly makes Palestinian see hope in a new day and find bliss  under all the destruction they see everyday.<ref name=\"rogerebert\" />\n* Is one of the first few Arabic films to be screened at [[Cannes Film Festival]] and more importantly one of the earliest Palestinian films to reach Cannes and gain a great deal of popularity, success and outstanding reviews. Affecting greatly the Arabic cinema and the Arab presence at [[Cannes]] by opening doors to many Palestinian and Arabic film directors to take on the same path and reach Cannes film festival.<ref name=\"albawaba\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Paradise now]]\n* [[Cinema of Palestine]]\n* [[Cinema Jenin]]\n* [[Palestinian National Theatre]]\n* [[Al-Kasaba Theatre]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Kjb6lIwDMDk Trailer], at YouTube\n\n{{Hany Abu-Assad}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Films about weddings]]\n[[Category:Palestinian films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Hany Abu-Assad]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2002 film}}\n{{Advert|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Rana's Wedding\n| image          = Rana's_Wedding.jpg\n| caption        = Poster\n| director       = [[Hany Abu-Assad]]\n| producer       = Bero Beyer and George Ibrahim\n| writer         = Ihab lamy and [[Liana Badr]]\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| editing        = Denise Janzee\n| starring       = [[Clara Khoury]], Khalifa Natour and Ismael Dabbagh\n| released       = {{Film date|2002}}\n| music          = Mariecke Van Der Linden and Bashar Abd Rabou\n| cinematography = Brigit Hillenius\n| distributor    = Arab Film Distribution\n| runtime        = 86 minutes\n| country        = Palestine\n| language       = Arabic\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $10,604<ref name=\"mojo\" /> (US)<!-- box office gross for US only, worldwide total not given -->\n}}\n'''''Rana's Wedding''''', also known as '''''Jerusalem, Another Day''''' (Arabic, \u0627\u0644\u0642\u062f\u0633 \u0641\u064a \u064a\u0648\u0645 \u0623\u062e\u0631 ), is a Palestinian film released in 2002, produced in partnership with the [[Netherlands]] and funded by the Palestinian Film Foundation. The film was shot in [[Jerusalem]] under the direction of  the Palestinian Director [[Hany Abu-Assad]] who is one of the first Palestinian film directors to reach [[Cannes Film Festival]] with his film, that was selected for screening at the [[International Critics' Week]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.itvs.org/about/global-perspectives-project/advisory-board |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512130925/http://itvs.org/about/global-perspectives-project/advisory-board |archive-date=2012-05-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"albawaba\">{{cite web|url=http://www.albawaba.com/entertainment/%E2%80%98rana%E2%80%99s-wedding%E2%80%99-opens-arab-presence-cannes-film-fest|title=\u2018Rana\u2019s Wedding\u2019 Opens Arab Presence at Cannes Film Fest|date=19 May 2002|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref> The film was also screened at multiple film festivals worldwide and received many excellent international reviews and awards. ''Rana's Wedding'' was able to present the [[Palestinian-Israeli conflict]] in an exceptional and compelling way, by using [[romance (love)|romance]] and [[dark comedy]] genres which left the audience astonished by this unique approach, that was able to portray, (through the couples marriage drama) a vivid image of a Palestinian's daily struggle, towards living a somewhat normal life.\n\n==Plot==\nA 17-year-old girl called Rana is subjected to a crucial life-changing decision at a very young age. Her father decides to leave Palestine and relocate to Egypt, due to the chaotic working and living conditions, to try to maintain a decent living to support his family. Rana wakes up one day and finds a letter from her father informing her about his difficult decision adding to it, he also involves her in his plans and provides her with two choices,<ref name=\"bostonglobe\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.boston.com/2004-03-12/ae/29207514_1_ihab-lamey-liana-badr-clara-khoury|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130118081234/http://articles.boston.com/2004-03-12/ae/29207514_1_ihab-lamey-liana-badr-clara-khoury|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 January 2013|title='Rana's Wedding' quietly marries passion, politics|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref> either to travel with him to Egypt and carry on with her education there under his watchful eye, or stay in Palestine and get married to make sure that someone is guarding her in his absence. Although the options seem fairly reasonable, there is a twist, her father will only allow her to marry one of the men that he has mentioned on a list with the letter, because they are the most reputable and trustworthy men in Jerusalem, as well as, she has to take that critical decision just 10 hours before her father departs from Palestine.<ref name=\"popmatters\">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/ranas-wedding|title=Rana's Wedding (2002)|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nRana is left shocked and disappointed with the options, after reading the letter she decides to run away from home in search of her lover Khalil that her father does not approve of because of his career, therefore, does not include him in the list of people she can marry.<ref name=\"bostonglobe\" /> Rana desperately searches for Khalil leaving no home, family or friend unasked about his whereabouts to inform him about her critical situation. As she searches for him she is faced with many challenges along the way from Israeli soldiers, road blocks and physical conflicts between Palestinian and Israeli soldiers.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C04E7DE1739F931A1575BC0A9659C8B63|title=Movie Review - 'Rana's Wedding' |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref> After hours of searching she finally finds his location and rushes to him, finding him in the theatre, working on directing one of his plays.\n\nAt last she finds him and tells him everything she has been through the past few hours, and confidently asks him for his hand in marriage, rushing him to take a decision in order to find a sheikh to marry them before her father sets off. Together they set out on an even longer journey to reach the sheikh and her father to approve of their marriage. They were able to find the sheikh and drove him to her father\u2019s house to convince him of the marriage, that he could not object to without any rightful excuse according to Islamic law, the sheikh supported Rana's decision and told her father that the marriage must proceed.<ref name=\"rogerebert\">{{cite web|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20040130/REVIEWS/401300304|title=Rana's Wedding Movie Review & Film Summary (2004) | website = RogerEbert.com | authorlink = Roger Ebert |first=Roger|last=Ebert|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref> Her father giving into her wishes unwillingly approves, Rana and Khalil then set out on another extremely tiresome mission, getting their papers and preparing themselves for their wedding ceremony.<ref name=\"filmthreat\">http://www.filmthreat.com/reviews/4693/</ref>\n\nAt the end tension rises when the wedding is held at Rana's father's house while the sheikh has not shown up to do the ceremony and her dad is getting ready to leave. As she waits restlessly she finds out that the sheikh is stuck at a road block. Her father gets furious and waits no longer, ordering her to come with him in her wedding dress, leaving for Egypt. Riding in the car with her father and her family they pressure and persuade her father to go to the road block for his daughter, finally agreeing they arrive at the road block. When her father and Khalil read their vows in the car, her dad sympathetically gives her away to the man she loves, ending the love story with a heart-warming celebration on the streets of Jerusalem. \n                                  \nThe film ends with the words of Palestinian poet, [[Mahmoud Darwish]]:\n{{quote|text=Here on the slopes before sunset and at the gun-mouth of time,\nNear orchards deprived of their shadows,<br />\nWe do what prisoners do,<br />\nWhat the unemployed do:<br />\nWe nurture hope.|sign=Mahmoud Darwish<ref name=\"popmatters\" />}}\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Clara Khoury]] as Rana\n* Khalifa Natour as Khalil\n* Ismael Dabbagh as Ramzy \n* Zuher Fahoum as Father\n* Bushra Karaman as Grandmother\n\n==Production==\nThe film was shot in [[East Jerusalem]], [[Ramallah]], [[State of Palestine|Palestine]]. Produced in collaboration with the [[Netherlands]] and funded by the Palestinian Film Foundation.<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\">{{cite web|url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ranas_wedding_jerusalem_another_day |title= Rana's Wedding: Jerusalem, Another Day|publisher= [[Fandango Media]] | website = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date= December 29, 2018 }}</ref> It was filmed  during a critical time in the early months of the [[second Palestinian intifada]]. [[Hany Abu-Assad]] in an interview with journalist Sabah Haider, discusses the challenges he faced when producing the film \"For sure the intifada influenced the production because at the end of the film, reality is stronger than fiction. The occupation, the checkpoints \u2014 you don\u2019t want them to interfere with your story but the ugliness of occupation influenced the look of film. As much as you might not want occupation to influence the making of the film, at the end it does influence it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electronicintifada.net/content/palestinian-cinema-cause-interview-hany-abu-assad/8708|title=\"Palestinian cinema is a cause\": an interview with Hany Abu-Assad|first=|last=matthew|date=8 March 2010|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nAccording to the website [[Box Office Mojo]], in 2003 ''Rana's Wedding'' was ranked out of the top 50 wedding genre films produced in that year, and received a world ranking of 1108 in [[foreign films]]. The film was able to generate $10,604 after 1 year of release, screening in film festivals around the world.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ranaswedding.htm|title=Rana's Wedding (2003) | website = [[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher= |access-date= 30 November 2016 }}</ref> It was selected for screening at the International critics week in 2002 at the [[Cannes Film Festival]].{{Citation needed|date = August 2015}}\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film ''Rana's Wedding'' was reviewed by many notable newspapers, websites and critics and overall received pleasing reviews.\n* ''Rana's Wedding'' was reviewed by [[Stephen Holden]] for ''[[The New York Times]]'' in 2003, discussing the plot and providing the film with great support to increase viewers interest towards this unique story.<ref name=\"nytimes\" />\n* It was reviewed by [[Al Bawaba]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albawaba.com/en/|title=Middle East News & Arab Headlines From A Local Perspective - Al Bawaba|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref> 2002, who identified it as one of the first Palestinian films to influence the Arabic films being screened at [[Cannes]] and was able to increase the Arab presence in the festival.<ref name=\"albawaba\" />\n* An article written by Janice Page in 2004 found at ''Boston''.com article collection, evaluates and supports the film with a great review.<ref name=\"bostonglobe\" />\n* ''[[About.com]]'', rated ''Rana's Wedding'', 3.5 stars out of 5, based on a review written by J\u00fcrgen Fauth, supporting the movie and evaluating its plot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldfilm.about.com/cs/filmsmiddleeast1/fr/ranaswedding.htm|title=Rana's Wedding|access-date=30 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201080108/http://worldfilm.about.com/cs/filmsmiddleeast1/fr/ranaswedding.htm|archive-date=1 December 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* On ''[[Rotten Tomatoes]]'' the film has an approval rating of 93% based on reviews from 28 critics, with an average rating of 7.2/10. The website's critical consensus states: \"A poignant drama that offers a look at what it is like to live in occupied Palestine.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\" />\n* On the website ''[[Metacritic]]'' the film has a score of 71 out of 100 based on reviews from 19 critics.<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web |url= http://www.metacritic.com/movie/ranas-wedding |title= Rana's Wedding |publisher= [[CBS Interactive]] | website = [[Metacritic]] |access-date= December 29, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n'''Awards'''\n* Won Grand Prize in Cologne  Mediterranean Film Festival, and [[Clara Khoury]] as best actress in (2002).<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web | url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0305229/awards |title= Rana's Wedding |date= 7 August 2003 |publisher= |work= IMDb |access-date=30 November 2016 }}</ref>\n* [[Clara Khoury]] won best actress from [[Marrakech International Film Festival]] in (2002).<ref name=\"imdb\" />\n* Won the Golden Antigone award from Montpellier Mediterranean Film Festival in (2002) <ref name=\"imdb\" />\n* Won the Golden Anchor award from [[Haifa International Film Festival]] in (2003) <ref name=\"imdb\" />\n* Won the [[Nestor Almendros]] for courage in film making, Human Rights Watch International Film Festival in (2003) \n'''Nominations'''\n* Nominated for the Golden star award from [[Marrakech International Film Festival]] in (2002)<ref name=\"imdb\" />\n* Nominated for the Golden Alexander Award by the [[Thessaloniki Film Festival]] in (2002)<ref name=\"imdb\" />\n* Nominated by [[Buenos Aires International Festival of Independent Cinema]] for Best Film in (2003) <ref name=\"imdb\" />\n* Nominated for Golden Dolphin award by [[Festr\u00f3ia - Tr\u00f3ia International Film Festival]] in (2003) <ref name=\"imdb\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n* ''Rana\u2019s Wedding'' is considered to be the first film that approaches and show cases the [[Palestinian-Israeli conflict]] in a novel way, leaving viewers astonished by this unique approach, because the film did not incorporate the common styles of films that discuss life circumstances in [[State of Palestine|Palestine]].<ref name=\"filmthreat\" /> In which they would always focus on tragic plots that contain similar content of war, murder, hunger and destruction. Instead ''Rana\u2019s Wedding'' portrayed all these events but in an indirect and compelling way, through a love story, and amazingly did not reduce the intensity of the Palestinian Israeli conflict. Through a plot that was able to portray how people still try to live and try to create an everyday normal life, despite the numbers that die in [[State of Palestine|Palestine]] each day. People still laugh, hope, worship, love, work, care for one other, sing and dance, and finally try to have a normal wedding that\u2019s not so normal to many of us.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiritualityandpractice.com/films/films.php?id=6542|title=Rana's Wedding - Film Reviews - Films - Spirituality & Practice|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref> ''Rana\u2019s Wedding'' is just filled with pure heart felt emotions and through the movements of the couple one is able to witness all the different events that take place in [[Jerusalem]], both the joyful and heart-breaking. A film that truly makes Palestinian see hope in a new day and find bliss  under all the destruction they see everyday.<ref name=\"rogerebert\" />\n* Is one of the first few Arabic films to be screened at [[Cannes Film Festival]] and more importantly one of the earliest Palestinian films to reach Cannes and gain a great deal of popularity, success and outstanding reviews. Affecting greatly the Arabic cinema and the Arab presence at [[Cannes]] by opening doors to many Palestinian and Arabic film directors to take on the same path and reach Cannes film festival.<ref name=\"albawaba\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Paradise now]]\n* [[Cinema of Palestine]]\n* [[Cinema Jenin]]\n* [[Palestinian National Theatre]]\n* [[Al-Kasaba Theatre]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Kjb6lIwDMDk Trailer], at YouTube\n\n{{Hany Abu-Assad}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Films about weddings]]\n[[Category:Palestinian films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Hany Abu-Assad]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rana%27s_Wedding"}
{"title_page": "Age Of Civilizations 2", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Age Of Civilizations 2|timestamp=20200408171529|year=2020|month=April|day=8|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Age Of Civilizations 2|date=8 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Age of Civilizations 2\n| developer = Lukasz Jakowski\n| series = Age of Civilizations\n| modes = Normal, Sandbox, Eternal War\n| genre = Grand Strategy Video Game\n| released = November 21, 2018\n}}\n\n'''''Age of Civilizations 2''' ('''AoC 2''')'' is a [[grand strategy]] [[video game]] developed entirely by \u0141ukasz Jakowski. It was initially released on November 21, 2018. It is the sequel to the original ''Age of Civilizations'' that was only available on mobile app stores. Like previous installment, ''Age of Civilizations 2'' is a [[grand strategy wargame]] with diverse historical eras serving as scenarios for the player to begin in. The player may take control of any nation in the world in one of the pre-installed scenarios or in a user-made scenario and lead it to victory or defeat against other countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ageofcivilizationsgame.com/aoc2.html|title=Age of Civilizations II, Reviews from Steam are: 9/10, Blue Moon Game's 4/5 - \u0141ukasz Jakowski Games|website=www.ageofcivilizationsgame.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Age Of Civilizations 2|timestamp=20200408171529|year=2020|month=April|day=8|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Age Of Civilizations 2|date=8 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n\n}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Age of Civilizations 2\n| developer = Lukasz Jakowski\n| series = Age of Civilizations\n| modes = Normal, Sandbox, Eternal War\n| genre = Grand Strategy Video Game\n| released = November 21, 2018\n}}\n\n'''''Age of Civilizations 2''' ('''AoC 2''')'' is a [[grand strategy]] [[video game]] developed entirely by \u0141ukasz Jakowski. It was initially released on November 21, 2018. It is the sequel to the original ''Age of Civilizations'' that was only available on mobile app stores. Like previous installment, ''Age of Civilizations 2'' is a [[grand strategy wargame]] with diverse historical eras serving as scenarios for the player to begin in. The player may take control of any nation in the world in one of the pre-installed scenarios or in a user-made scenario and lead it to victory or defeat against other countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ageofcivilizationsgame.com/aoc2.html|title=Age of Civilizations II, Reviews from Steam are: 9/10, Blue Moon Game's 4/5 - \u0141ukasz Jakowski Games|website=www.ageofcivilizationsgame.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Age_Of_Civilizations_2"}
